'''Apollo 11''' was the [[spaceflight]] that landed the first humans on Earth's [[Moon]] on July 20, 1969 (20:17:40 [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]]). The mission, carried out by the [[United States]], is considered a major accomplishment in the history of exploration.

Launched from [[Florida]] on July 16, the fifth manned mission, and the third lunar mission of [[NASA]]'s [[Apollo program]], was crewed by Commander [[Neil Armstrong]], Command Module Pilot [[Michael Collins (astronaut)|Michael Collins]], and Lunar Module Pilot [[Buzz Aldrin|Edwin &quot;Buzz&quot; Aldrin, Jr]]. On July 20, Armstrong and Aldrin landed in the [[Mare Tranquillitatis|Sea of Tranquility]] and on July 21 became the first humans to walk on the Moon. Their [[lunar module|landing craft]], ''Eagle'', spent 21 hours and 31 minutes on the lunar surface while Collins orbited above in the [[Apollo Command/Service Module|command ship]], ''Columbia''.&lt;ref&gt;[http://history.nasa.gov/SP-4029/Apollo_11i_Timeline.htm NASA Apollo 11 Timeline].&lt;/ref&gt; The three astronauts returned to Earth with {{convert|47.5|lb|kg}} of lunar rocks and landed in the [[Pacific Ocean]] on July 24.

Apollo 11 fulfilled U.S. President [[John F. Kennedy]]'s goal of reaching the Moon before the [[Soviet Union]] by the end of the 1960s, which he had expressed during a 1961 [[Apollo program#Background|mission statement]] before the [[United States Congress]]: &quot;I believe that this nation should commit itself to achieving the goal, before this decade is out, of landing a man on the Moon and returning him safely to the Earth.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news|url=http://archives.cnn.com/2001/TECH/space/05/25/kennedy.moon/ |title=Man on the moon: Kennedy speech ignited the dream |work=CNN | first=Richard | last=Stenger | date=May 25, 2001 | accessdate=March 30, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Five additional Apollo missions landed on the Moon from 1969 to 1972.

